<taxonomicName authority="Yakovlev &amp; Saldaitis" authorityName="Yakovlev &amp; Saldaitis" authorityYear="2016" box="[708,1062,185,209]" class="Insecta" family="Cossidae" genus="Vartiania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="394" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beludzhi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[708,825,185,209]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">V. beludzhi</emphasis>
Yakovlev &amp; Saldaitis
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1069,1156,186,210]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1069,1156,186,210]" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
The species of this genus are typical representatives of the southwestern Palearctic deserts, distributed from the southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1186,1306,221,244]" name="Uzbekistan" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Uzbekistan</collectingCountry>
to southern 
<collectingCountry box="[151,245,256,279]" name="Pakistan" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
. Externally the new species differs from all the representatives of the genus by the grey colour of wings and the weakly developed pattern on the male forewing. The external characters of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yakovlev" authorityYear="2004" box="[970,1107,290,313]" class="Insecta" family="Cossidae" genus="Vartiania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="394" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zaratustra">
<emphasis box="[970,1107,290,313]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">V. zaratustra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1122,1226,290,313]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1 − 5" captionStart-1="FIGURES 6 − 14" captionStartId-0="1.[151,258,1892,1914]" captionStartId-1="2.[151,258,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox-0="[224,1350,535,1868]" captionTargetBox-1="[267,1309,206,1740]" captionTargetId-0="figure@1.[212,1364,523,1876]" captionTargetId-1="figure@2.[255,1324,191,1744]" captionTargetPageId-0="1" captionTargetPageId-1="2" captionText-0="FIGURES 1 − 5. Vartiania, adults and male genitalia: 1. V. beludzhi Yakovlev &amp; Saldaitis sp. nov. holotype, male; 2. V. beludzhi Yakovlev &amp; Saldaitis sp. nov., paratype, female; 3. Male genitalia of V. beludzhi Yakovlev &amp; Saldaitis sp. nov. (holotype, GenPR MWM: 25260); 4. V. zaratustra, holotype, male, S. Iran, Hormozgan Prov., Beshagerd Mts., Davari, 600 m, 26 ° 34 N, 57 ° 54 E, 6 − 11.04.2000, leg. V. Siniaev &amp; A. Plutenko (Museum Witt, München); 5. Male genitalia of V. zaratustra (paratype, GenPR MWM: 9282)." captionText-1="FIGURES 6 − 14. Dervishiya, adults and male genitalia: 6. D. sindhi Yakovlev &amp; Saldaitis sp. nov. holotype, male; 7. D. sindhi Yakovlev &amp; Saldaitis sp. nov., paratype, male, Pakistan, Sindh prov., near Sanghar, Shahdadpur, 28. 0 3. 2009, leg. Azeemi (Museum Witt, München); 8. D. sindhi Yakovlev &amp; Saldaitis sp. nov., paratype, female, Pakistan, Sindh prov., Mirpurkhas, 20. 0 3. 2009, leg. Azeemi (Museum Witt, München); 9. Male genitalia of D. sindhi Yakovlev &amp; Saldaitis sp. nov. (paratype, GenPR MWM: 25303); 10. D. cadambae Moore, 1865, male, syntype (Museum für Naturkunde, Leibniz Institut für Evolution und Biodiversitätsforschung, Berlin); 11. D. cadambae Moore, 1865, female, syntype (Natural History Museum, London); 12. Male genitalia of D. cadambae Moore, 1865 (Pakistan, Indus Kohistan, GenPR MWM: 25302); 13. D. vartianae Yakovlev, 2011, male, paratype (Naturhistorisches Museum, Wien); 14. D. vartianae Yakovlev, 2011, female, paratype (Naturhistorisches Museum, Wien)." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/1050837/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/1050839/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="394">Figs. 4−6</figureCitation>
) are mostly typical for this genus, but have several peculiar features: the developed reticulated dark pattern of the forewing; the strongly sclerotized protuberance at the costal margin of the valva; the narrow juxta with pointed apices, narrow lateral juxta processes with pointed apices tapered at acute angle; the phallus thick, with more developed preapical spinous processes at the vesica aperture margins.
</paragraph>
